segments.text: So anyway, if we could begin.
You just sort of introduce yourself, and you don't need to talk into the mic.
It's real good.
It picks up all kinds of stuff.
It picks up right there.
OK, my name is Bill Kendrick.
I was raised in central part of Texas, up near Burnett.
I went to Southwest Texas State in San Marcos.
And after that, I got a job with the Soil Conservation Service.
What did you major in?
In agronomy.
And when I worked for the Soil Conservation Service, I was in the position of a soil scientist.
And we did...
When was this?
When did you go to school?
When did you graduate?
This was in the mid-60s, 65, 66.
Oh, but I knew the deputy director of the soil conservation service for a very long time, Jeff Dykes, who, I don't know whether you knew him or not, he was from Washington, D.C. Old egg.
No, I guess I knew him.
I was working up in...
He retired maybe about the time you joined.
I was working up in Comanche.

county doing a progressive soil survey of that county and it was in the late 60s i guess by that time i'd been with the service about seven years that they were getting to to formulate the woodlands and put it together and the environmental planners uh particularly when you talk about that you think of ian mccard right that wrote the book design with nature they wanted
One of the things that they needed was the soils information.

And so being the young progressive soil scientist, I guess, up in Comanche County, the Soil Conservation Service was looking for someone to come to the woodlands, at that time we're talking about 20,000 acres, and be a party leader to map out the existing soils that occurred in the woodlands.
So as part of the environmental impact statement and part of the original HUD
HUD application and part of that plan.

So I got selected to come down and it was kind of an unusual agreement that the federal government could not go and do work on private lands and do a survey that had already been completed at a larger scale as part of the Montgomery County soil survey.
So what they did, they kind of contracted us through the local salt and water conservation district
And we in turn, through the district, we were able to work in the woodlands.
So we came in and spent about almost a year.
I guess I moved to Conroe then in 1972.
And we spent about a year in the field mapping out the different soil types and observing and recording the different vegetation types that was occurring on the soil.
After we finished the field work, at the same time we were doing water percolation tests and we had water table studies where we were doing some little shallow wells and doing that.
And we were having visits and corresponding with McCarg and his planners, working along with them at the same time.
Then we had to finish up the report after we did the field work.
And I was finishing that up and
ready to move on to something else, and I was offered a job to go work with the Woodlands Corporation to stay around and help them interpret and understand.
Who did it?
Who offered me the job.
The person who was leading, hitting up that part of the planning at the time was James Beltman, or Jim Beltman.

and he was kind of the liaison between the corporation and mccard and his people so he thought i should be part of the team to stay around and do that so he offered me a job and at the time it was a rough decision to give up my security of working with the federal government to come to work with the developer this was about when this was in 19 i actually came to work in 1973. okay
You've been here a long time.
I've been here a long time.
The Woodlands didn't open until 1974.
So I came to work with them and immediately fell into the job of working with the planters and trying to explain the different soil types and what we'd expect from a development.
They were concerned about runoff and recharge and all those percolation rate of soils and we did some of that.

then it was like well you know what am i going to do now so i got involved in the in the tree preservation aspect of the woodlands because of that earlier experience of mapping out the vegetation and having that knowledge of the different kinds of trees and agronomy knowledge so the concern and the challenge from mr mitchell from the early days was to develop a new town and not disturb the character of the forest
which meant that we were going to try to save every tree we possibly could.
We were not going to destroy what we call the understory of the big trees, the canopy trees with the overstory and everything underneath was the understory.
The brush.
Where you get your screen and where you get your flowering plants like dogwoods and sassafras and all that kind of thing.
So that was...
I think one of the most significant, from the appearance of the Woodlands today, I think that was a significant decision.
It was not going to be a park-like environment where you go in and just leave the mature trees and clear the understory.
And based on the premise that we were going to try to utilize the natural forest as much as we could, so it's a lot cheaper and it just makes more sense to

to save what you have, groom and prune and work with that and replace with native plant material as opposed to cut everything down and bring in something completely foreign and plastic looking and plant that.
So, you know, it's working with the existing plant.
So I was given the job of the tree keeper and so I ended up working with the individual builders

that came to the Woodlands and we actually went out and required the builders to outline the footprint, whether it was a single family or whether it was a commercial structure, to outline the footprint.
If they were going to clear, then we...
They'd actually stake it out?
Stake out the footprint and the driveway and with a continuous ribbon all the way around and then
we would either approve or disapprove an issue of clearing permit if everything was properly marked out.
And we would make decisions at that time, can we shift the house to the front or to the rear, and can we move things over to save a few trees.

So we were successful in saving a lot of trees simply because of offsets in the house that maybe they didn't take advantage of, or maybe flipping and putting the driveway on the other side and doing those kinds of things.

and but once we said okay now you can clear so they go in and they get so bad it's it's always been rewarded for being as as fast and as reckless as you can the fact you clear the better you are the dozer operator the dozer operator so uh he just started falling trees and they were going outside the ribbon and everywhere so we

had a real education process with all the subcontractors in the woodlands as to how we wanted them to try to protect the forest it was they were just not accustomed to doing anything that drastic but tedious as far as keeping let me explore that just a little bit um manifestly what you're talking about is something well in fact what you're saying is this was not a normal
way of doing business.
Usually when a builder goes in, it's his convenience to serve first in terms of building a home, because that lowers his costs, that he can do it more efficiently.
Do strip clearing and build a pad.
And from here's point of view, even more effectively, really, than what you're suggesting.
So that education process had to be fairly formable, I would think.
Could you explain a little bit about one
how that education process developed, the role you played in it, to how successful it was.
Was there a builder fallout?
Were there some builders that said, I ain't going to do this, and wandered off?
Were there times when, in fact, you mentioned that you gave them approval.
What happened when they didn't get approval?
Builders sometimes work on a very marginal kind of profit.
Delays, what have you, could seriously disrupt or affect their success?
How did you deal with those kinds of things?
I guess the most beneficial two we had to work with was as the different sections were developed.
They were described and they were so under covenant that the
the development criteria for that section spelled out that the vegetation would be preserved.
It was kind of a binding agreement with them.
We had a lot of problems with the builders who were coming out of Houston in the 1960s and coming out here and they'd never done things like this before.
They didn't like the delays.
They didn't like putting up the fencing.
We had a lot of real heated arguments
with some of the builders to the point where, you know, they just almost want to fight.
They'd get so mad at you.
And we ended up kind of having a, taken back through DSC.
They had a committee called DSC, which was Development Standards Committee.
Yeah.
That approved the single family plans and that aspect.
And there were many meetings where we would, it had the support of management, what we were trying to do.
And we would have meetings where we would present, maybe I would put together a slide show and those kind of things, and we would meet and present it to the builders.
We would not only present it to the builders, but we'd present it to their people that they used as landscape.
You know, we'd invite all of the landscape people and all of the builders and all of the cleanup men, which probably had more decision than any of us in what it actually looked like in the end.
actually doing the cleanup and putting down the saw and doing the grading.
You know, the lowest paid person on the staff was the one that was making the final decision as to the survival of my little wishes, the brush.
But it was that kind of, those kind of meetings, and again, it had support of Mr. Mitchell on down, and that was what the Williams was going to do like, you know.
And it was basically just, you know, either build like we want you to build or go somewhere else, you know.
It was kind of a...
the builders were, we weren't just selling lots to everyone, you know, it was kind of a select group of people that were here.
They had to have a track record proving, you know, they built a good house and those kind of things.
So it was a good situation to be in.
I felt like we always had the upper hand and had control.
If they over cleared, then we tried to force them to replant.
And it was a lot of

have so far involved when you didn't abide by the rules we required after clearing after you got to that point then you had all the subcontractors that want to go through the woods and tear up the forest so we found out we can't have that because we're not going to have anything so we required them to put up in the early days in this training process this is like in the 70s or not mid 70s this is some of the first homes we built down in
all across some settler's corner town halls where the first models of the woodlands were that I'm thinking about.
We required them to put up fencing right inside that envelope.
And they didn't want to do that.
In some cases we actually went in and put up the fence ourselves to help protect the vegetation of the first models that we built to make the point that we were trying to get across.
And
We were successful in doing that.

And once, after they built the homes there and they got rid of the landscape, we insisted, too, on approval of the landscape plan so that they would maintain the natural character again, use, you know, indigenous plants or use native plants that would fit in and texture and blend in with the existing mature trees that were there.
So, you know, when the models opened, we were all very proud of the way they looked.

literally just tucked into the woods at the end of a cul-de-sac and it was very popular a lot of people really liked that concept but there were still those in the sales force and they were skeptical about what it would really working on you know the place looked like it's not being maintained it looks like we need to mow along with the streets and anytime the sales were down they always blamed it on signage and landscape you know that was why we were not selling homes
I mean first impressions.
First impression that you get when you come into the Woodlands.

But Mr. Mitchell was very persistent about that was what the Woodlands was going to be like and we were going to save the forest and so the problem you had then was once you sell that home to someone he wants to come in and because of that nature and that natural instinct to get out and
and clear his block of land and develop the way he's always seen it with St. Augustine grass and curb appeal to my house.
The first weekend is there, he takes his saw, his machete, and he comes down and he wants to chop up everything that we've been beating the builders over the head about for five, six months to save.
He clears it out the first weekend and puts it on the curb and gets someone to haul it off the next week.
So we thought, how do we overcome that one?
We actually went around in the early days and visited with the residents.
We'd have native landscape seminars for all the residents of the woodlands.
In the early days we had a wildflower conference, I think we called it, where we would put people on bus tours and drive them around.
and identify wildflowers to build that kind of interest that you had.
And it was, you know, those that were very, the little ladies in tennis shoes and the very ecology-minded people were the easiest ones to sell.
But those that had prior homes and lived in a more suburban area were the most difficult to sell.
And, you know, our theory was that if you could just get someone to, you know, to wait a season

before you chop anything down and be inside your glass home and look out like we're looking out now into this area and watch it change through the seasons and watch the flowering of the dogwoods and the berries, the beauty berries and all those things develop.
Then you develop that appreciation for it.
And we always insisted everyone go through the information center, which is a multimedia presentation on that one.
And we developed a nature trail

by the information center also and we had a brochure that went along with the trail and it was open to all the residents and it explained our concept for development and how important it was to keep it foraged and how
But, you know, so many trees in front of your house increase the value 27%, you know, a lot of value.
And how important it was to the environment and to the birds and the wildlife and all that.
And let them begin to identify the trees and there was a posted number and it told you the common and botanical name.
And just try to instill that sense of real feeling that we had about how important it was to development.
Keep that character.
Yeah, I appreciate it.
Do you know...
I forgot how to ask this question.
Playing devil's advocate, let's say I move here from East Orange, New Jersey.
For whatever reasons, I buy...
home or buy a lot in the woodlands and build on it.
And then Bill Kendrick or somebody comes and tells me about how I should be landscaping it.
With certain kinds of personalities, there might be some resistance to anyone telling me what to do with my land.
You know what I'm saying?
Exactly.

How many, I guess, of the people you talked to were, to borrow a religious phrase, converted to Mr. Mitchell's vision versus those who said, I ain't going to do it, versus those who said, we moved and then went somewhere else.
Do you understand what I'm saying?
How successful, I guess I'm trying to ask, was that?
a combination of educational slash propagandizing, and I mean that in a positive sense, effort.
Do you have any feel for that at all?
Well, I think the best way to answer the question, if you could, the village of Grover's Mill was the first one we did.
And if you could drive back through Grover's Mill in sections one, two, three, four, five, six, and seven, you know, those are the first ones.
You can't see the houses where the trees.
I mean, it's literally very successful.
There was always a few.
And that's true in any situation.
But I'd say 90% successful.
To me, success meant if you drove down the street
There was always a native look to the landscaping.
The mature trees were there, there was a certain amount of understory.
I consider we were successful if we had a natural block of forest opposite side of the driveway that was not completely destroyed and cleared out and installed to St. Augustine grass.
They enjoyed, I think, the privacy that you get from leaving it in the backyard so you don't see your neighbor's swing set, so you don't see a row of houses.
It's kind of that little secluded bit of privacy that you get.
What you have to remember, things were a little bit slow in those days in 74.
They weren't a little bit slow.
They were real slow.
It's almost like you built a new town but no one came.
So you had the opportunity to work.
one-on-one with a homeowner, art builder, and you're not in the fast pace that you're in today.
So you're able to spend more time with them and then do a better job of that conversion experience that we're talking about.
Does that still continue today?
Are you still doing this in 1991?
It's still just as important to Mr. Mitchell and management as it's ever been.
I understand that, but how is it accomplished?
Today it's, we have a, we don't go door to door and try to talk to new homeowners.
The builder still gets beat over the head just as hard as he ever did about doing his part.
We have a, at the information center, they hand out a residential guide to landscaping in the woodlands, something we developed to show them how to.
May I have this?
Yes.
Thank you.
How to try to save the, try to save the forest.
It's handed out there.
There's all kinds of information that they get when they move to the Woodlands.
It's like the welcome wagon or the newcomer approach to it.
It's included in that.
There's still slideshows and presentations to landscapers and builders today.
And I think probably more than anything, it's probably enforced just the feeling that you get when you drive into the Woodlands by the people.
The best effort is probably made by the people that live here now.
Tim probably told you.
I sensed that, yeah.
I don't know, I seem like it's, I don't remember the number, at least 25 or 30% probably of the new home sales or referrals from people living here now.
And it's just a pride that the community has.
I mean, you know, if somebody really get on your case now about tearing up trees, it's the residents against the developer, you know.
And it's a good position to be in.
Tim also mentioned that just since 1985, over 50% of the builders have packed it in and left.
So I assume you're having a continuing education program with those new builders as well.
Yes, it's always...
From day one, it's been a problem.
Not just the builders, but from the subcontractors.
Those are drivers that left, you know, or knew and came in.
You had to go through the same process again.
My role has changed.
Now since I'm manager of grounds maintenance, I'm not working with the builders or the residents in that respect.
You know, we're concentrating on kind of out of that field that we're talking about.
that I wasn't doing at that time.
I'm doing something different.
Well, that's good.
Let's shift gears.
What are you doing now?
How does your role fit?
How long have you been doing this, manager of grounds maintenance?
This is about the fourth year.
It's kind of my five years now.
Okay, okay.
Was there a predecessor to you?
Was it a position created for you?
Was there someone who was...
There was someone here, and he retired.
Oh, okay.
So you inherited a...
Well, philosophy obviously has already existed, but you inherited some procedures and activities.
What challenges, changes, like I said, benchmarks have occurred in the last 10 years in what is your job?
I think one thing I didn't mention
Now we're involved in not working on individual lots, but we're working on all the company-owned properties, anything the company owns, and we maintain it.
We landscape it.
We maintain all of the street right-of-ways.
And one of the significant things we've been able to do there is the utilization of the natural reforestation, which simply says that
If you've got a grass that you're mowing there every day and a little pine tree sticks its head up and you cut it off, it never has an opportunity to grow back.
So many areas that we can, we go in and do a planting of native plant material and let Mother Nature come back and heal those scars.
And our concept oversimplified is to
to hide the unsightly parts and accentuate all the pluses and the beauty.
And that's kind of our, and using native plant material, you know, that's our philosophy.
I think one of the most popular things we've done is the development of our Woodlands Wildflower Program that we have.
grown to the point where this year we probably planted about $20,000 worth of wildflower seeds.
Probably one of the biggest plantings that occurs anywhere in the state of Texas.
We bought over, planted about 2,000 pounds of bluebonnet seed, which is a lot of bluebonnets.
And what we've seen is that has really grown in interest.
And with Mr. Mitchell's encouragement,
We're not only doing that here in the Woodlands, but we're trying to encourage other people to do this.
For instance, the Hardy Toll Road, we've gone down and did some plantings on the Hardy Toll Road.
Your office is down there?
Right.
From the Woodlands Corporation.
They provided the seed, and we actually go do the planting for them.
He asked us to go down to Rice University, and we did some demonstration plantings down there.
pray to sow the seed and, you know, they'll reap the benefits.
On the Beltway 8, for the Houston Lighting and Power, they provided the seed and we went and did some plantings underneath some of their power lines.
There's a test project.
He believes that, you know, if we can have other people do what we're doing, from a natural landscaping, for wildlife programs, then we're all the benefit of that.
And, um...
and it's been successful.
I've got a letter on my desk today that came from the Hardy Toll Road.
It went to Mr. Mitchell, thanking him for our efforts in establishing the wildfire from Hardy Toll Road.
The company, we also maintain and do work in the Galveston area on some of our property as manager of grounds maintenance.
And he's big on getting wildfire established in some of the developments in the Galveston area also.
Do you go to Colorado to Snowmass?
No, I haven't been up there.
No, it's just been in this area.
So that's been a major, obviously a major impetus.
Right.
What other things are hanging out there?
If someone, you know, what I'm looking for, obviously, or maybe it's not obvious, but in 20 years people are going to look back and say,
boy, that really made a difference when we did this or when we did that or when this was allowed to happen or that occurred.

What sort of things are going on and have gone on within the decade of the 80s and presently that, you know, the business as usual stuff, people are going to know about, but what changes, what initiatives
anything, I mean, business as usual has been so successful, I really can't think of anything really new and outstanding that we're doing.
Or have there been significant challenges to the business as usual?
That have, that have, you know, where you've had to, you know, mount troops in charge?
Yeah.
Um, no, just the, um, the size of the jobs that we've had to complete.
And I think I see a little bit of, um,
of refinement.
There's still that battle of is it properly maintained from a first impression, from a buyer's standpoint.
I think there's a little bit of more of a grooming appearance, more of a little strip of grass along the edge of the wood to give you that transition.
So you kind of lose that weedy look along the edge.
I think that's the trend.
We're doing a little bit more material.
Economics have played into that too, haven't they?
One of the things Tim was telling me was that in the downturn times, 82, 83, 84, 86, through there when things were rough, they were selling 300, 400 homes a year or something like that.
Now they're selling 900,000.
And they're looking to do that in good times.
And that they're promoting the notion that builders will finish out 600 homes, all within each other.
And they want to do that as a marketing plan.
Which means that instead of having homes built serially, you'll have huge blocks, whole neighborhoods done.
Has that brought distinct challenges, different challenges?
I think just in volume of work that we had to do, and the staff increase.
I mean, my staff has grown from, since I've been here, from 30 and 35 to, I think we had like 80 at the peak period this year.
And it fluctuates.
We have an average of 55, and this next year I might have an average of 60.
and just the keeping up with the staff and the motivation and keeping the equipment that you need and just actually getting the job done.
It's just such a, the area's growing.
Everything we have installed since 1974, I still have to maintain that, plus everything new that we're installing.
So it's getting to be big.
It's just geometric increases, right?
I think one of the things that we're trying to do is to
from a landscape standpoint, are to not install so many of those things that are high labor items.
I mean, there's a big issue in management about color or no color.
If we start installing hundreds of median tips I have all over the Woodlands now, if I put color in those areas, then my staff is going to probably double just to do the
the hand labor that's involved in doing that.
So, you know, we're saying stay with native plants, minimum kind of maintenance.
What color are you talking about?
Annual?
Annual color that you'd replace two or three times a year based upon the season.
And that's kind of an ongoing battle right now.
And I think it's...
Between whom?
Between...
Those of us that are maybe too pure, the naturalist versus the sales, the marketing staff.
They're doing it in 1960, so we should be doing it out here.
Some of us think, well, go to 1960.
That's why we're unique is because we're different.
From little things that we are seeing, we've picked out a beautiful red maple.

okay when it had extremely good color and about it and we we're working with one of the growers and we're growing our own calling the woodlands red maple and we hope to proliferate the woodlands with our our red maple and you know someday it may be something you go to a nursery and buy you know those little kind of things are going on but from an overall standpoint we're we're looking into techniques and ways to
keep down the maintenance costs so we can afford to keep doing all the maintenance that we are now.
Well, that makes sense from a management point of view.
The marketers, though, I would imagine, you know, I mean, I understand or I assume from what you said that this battle, to use your words, is not over.
This discussion is ongoing.
What if the marketing group wins and, in fact, there is color in all the tips of these things?
What will that mean besides just more work?
I think it would mean more work.
I think it would be, I don't know what the total outcome would be.
You know, if that was all we did, I think that we could live through that.
My concern would be that we'd get to the point someday, if you let your guard down.
I mean, to me, you've got to try to save 100% of the trees on the block or the lot that you're working with.
or you won't get them.
If you try to save 100%, then you may get 50 or 60%.
If you loosen your requirements and you say, well, let's strive for 50, you're going to get 25.
And my real concern would be if we ever relaxed our rules, our demands on keeping the character of the forest, that forest is like people, like old people,

If you just save the big trees, mature trees, you don't save all of the, to me it's understory and the shrubs, and we called it brush earlier, with the beauty part of the forest, and it's also where those child trees and the little trees are coming along.

If you ever get to the point where you say, okay, let's mow that and make it look more like a park as opposed to a living forest, then in time, we're going to deplete the forest because old trees are going to die, and there's not going to be anything there
to replace it and I think it would be the most critical error that we could make if we got to the point where we actually destroy the character of our living forest that we have today.
So you obviously favor a conservative or a conservationist point of view, let's conserve what we have rather than muddy the water with new introductions and new species.
Absolutely, absolutely.
We might, I think you can have

you can possibly have both if you say okay it's okay we're going to touch up the median tips and lightly but you still got to be just as strong about the forest itself I mean a median tip is in the middle of the road so it's not a great reforestation zone or regenerative area where you're you know you're trying to keep the character of the forest but I think once it starts on the if you're
relax and it starts on the median tips and the next thing it's going to start is around the office building.
I want them to be able to see my signs.
I want them to be able to see my building.
So we start, it's a constant battle.
We have it with every new commercial building.
We just had a McDonald's that they said, you know, you can't have a McDonald's if you can't see the sign for 10 miles away.
But it's not.
It's not that way.
It has a low-profile sign, and you have to know where it is to get there.
And to everyone's surprise, especially the owner, it's outperforming all the other McDonald's in the area.
So we have that kind of debate going on.
Are you going to have to, whenever we get out on I-45, are you going to have to be able to see the signs in the commercial part of the woodlands?
We're five miles in both directions.
Right now we're saying no.
But there's another side to that, too.
If you know where it is, you're going to come.
Because I've talked to individuals who said that from a marketing point of view, and again, it's marketers.
They're the ones who are concerned about image as much as you are, only from a different point of view.
One gentleman, I'm trying to think who it was.
It may have been Richard Brown.
Although I could be wrong about that.
But anyway, one gentleman I know mentioned he says one of the mistakes he thinks was made
was that instead of having a wall of trees on I-45, that in fact there should have been a peak into a lake.
I think there will be.
It just hasn't happened.
Yeah.
But he says it should have happened from day one.
That there should have been something intriguing from I-45 about the woodlands, rather than this sort of closed... You know, because the forest has two images.
They're in constant conflict.
One is the nurturing trees, the sheltering canopy, the privacy, the noise abatement.
The other is the forbidding woods.
You can't see the forest with trees.
That's right.
That's where the bears live.
That's where the wolves live.
You know what I'm saying?
There's a forbidding...
for some claustrophobic concern about it.
And the notion was, well, hey, from I-45, all you see is this wall.
And it seems impenetrable.
And it seems, or it can seem daunting, perhaps.
Maybe that's not the word.
I think you might get that sense now as you drive.
by the woodlands on I-45.
We don't really see that much going on.
I think they have tried, we have tried, we just haven't been able to develop that commercial portion of the woodlands.
The population base hasn't been here to get them all and those kind of things.
But it's right on the verge of happening.
The next few years it's going to explode along the entry to I-45.
One of the things you will see there someday will be our impression of
This is the woodlands, and you're going to look through the trees or underneath the trees and look into that lake that you're talking about.
It's going to be there, and I think it'll be well done.
The problem, as I see it, is not the view of the lake.

The reason you keep those trees out there now and that wall is there is to give you an option, again, to open up those little peaks so you can see in and to hide those cars that are going to be in front of the mall.
And I think that's the challenge.
is how do we keep it from looking like the other side of the street where all you see is buildings and concrete and asphalt.
That's what I want it to look like.
Still be enough of those little contiguous pieces of forest even though there's parking lots and cars and buildings and service stations and all those kind of things are going to be there.
It still gives you the warmth
of the woods when you drive by there, that this is a rule.
